{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3329464,"name":"Greg","username":"JoeFizzy","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/958977/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-11T00:45:18.255Z","cooked":"<p>We’re making good progress with YAGSL and PathPlanner in our first year using the tools, but we’re still facing some accuracy issues.</p>
<p>Today, we created a simple path that ran from the field wall to the first blue line. The robot consistently stopped right at the line (good x-coordinate), but the Y-coordinate varied over 10 trials by about 14". Additionally, the robot rotation was off by a few degrees in all but one of the tests (see PathPlanner screenshot below). In theory, the robot should drive completely straight, but inevitably, it has a little oscillation in it’s rotation.</p>
<p><div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/e/f/eff1eea0aa8afc02d376c1b26be35c4984ceffb2.png" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/eff1eea0aa8afc02d376c1b26be35c4984ceffb2" title="20240310-straightpath-4"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/e/f/eff1eea0aa8afc02d376c1b26be35c4984ceffb2_2_690x388.png" alt="20240310-straightpath-4" data-base62-sha1="yeEs40ivvRukIXCiwy2Xjs6xJwC" width="690" height="388" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/e/f/eff1eea0aa8afc02d376c1b26be35c4984ceffb2_2_690x388.png, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/e/f/eff1eea0aa8afc02d376c1b26be35c4984ceffb2_2_1035x582.png 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/e/f/eff1eea0aa8afc02d376c1b26be35c4984ceffb2_2_1380x776.png 2x" data-dominant-color="232329"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">20240310-straightpath-4</span><span class="informations">1920×1080 306 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>
<p>I am assuming this is a <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> issue based on the charts displayed. Our PathPlanner <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> section is quoted below:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public void setupPathPlanner() {
    AutoBuilder.configureHolonomic(
        this::getPose, // Robot pose supplier
        this::resetOdometry, // Method to reset odometry (will be called if your auto has a starting pose)
        this::getRobotVelocity, // ChassisSpeeds supplier. MUST BE ROBOT RELATIVE
        this::setChassisSpeeds, // Method that will drive the robot given ROBOT RELATIVE ChassisSpeeds
        new HolonomicPathFollowerConfig( // HolonomicPathFollowerConfig, this should likely live in your Constants class
        // Translation PID constants
            new PIDConstants(7.5, 0.0, 0.0),
            // Rotation PID constants
            new PIDConstants(7.5, 0.0, 0.0),
            // Max module speed, in m/s
            4,
            swerveDrive.swerveDriveConfiguration.getDriveBaseRadiusMeters(),

            // Drive base radius in meters. Distance from robot center to furthest module.
            new ReplanningConfig()
        // Default path replanning config. See the API for the options here
        ),
        () -&gt; {
          // Boolean supplier that controls when the path will be mirrored for the red
          // alliance
          // This will flip the path being followed to the red side of the field.
          // THE ORIGIN WILL REMAIN ON THE BLUE SIDE
          var alliance = DriverStation.getAlliance();
          return alliance.isPresent() ? alliance.get() == DriverStation.Alliance.Red : false;
        },
        this // Reference to this subsystem to set requirements
    );
  }
</code></pre>
<p>Does this look like a <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> issue? If so, is it likely the PP <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> coefficients, or the YAGSL <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> coefficients? Does anyone have any ideas on how to get this to be more accurate?</p>
<p>Thanks in advance for your help-</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":4,"updated_at":"2024-03-11T00:45:18.255Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":86,"reads":55,"readers_count":54,"score":441.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":458182,"topic_slug":"path-following-error-with-pathplanner-and-yagsl","display_username":"Greg","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/e/f/eff1eea0aa8afc02d376c1b26be35c4984ceffb2.png","internal":true,"reflection":false,"clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":62319,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/path-following-error-with-pathplanner-and-yagsl/458182/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3329781,"name":"","username":"nstrike","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/nstrike/{size}/167038_2.png","created_at":"2024-03-11T12:15:10.470Z","cooked":"<p>This is more than likely a <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> issue with pathplanner, you should definitely continue to tune it! You may also want to lower your maximum drive velocity just to be sure.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":4,"updated_at":"2024-03-11T12:15:10.470Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_numb